LIST:- 
it is a collection of items which is stored in a variable , and the items are stored in a order.

List is a mutable datatype, we can further make changes in this

Ex:- x=["Vivek",22,"CSE","Python"]

Python has 11 built-in methods used to manipulate and interact with lists. 

Adding Elements:

append(): Adds an element to the end of the list.
extend(): Adds all elements of another iterable (like a list) to the end.
insert(): Adds an element at a specific index position. 

Removing Elements:

pop(): Removes and returns the element at a given position (defaults to the last item).
remove(): Removes the first occurrence of a specific value.
clear(): Removes all elements, leaving the list completely empty. 

Finding and Counting Elements:

index(): Returns the index position of the first occurrence of a specific value.
count(): Returns the total number of times a specific value appears in the list. 

Ordering and Copying:

sort(): Sorts the items of the list in place (ascending by default).
reverse(): Reverses the order of the items in place.
copy(): Returns a shallow copy of the entire list. 
